d 'NAAM': module for consistent string encoding, ID hashing, and label management
d
d  naam ("What's in a naam?") addresses a common problem in
d  large-scale survey and administrative data work: encoding string
d  variables consistently across multiple files. Stata's native
d  encode assigns codes alphabetically within each dataset, meaning
d  codes shift whenever a new category appears in a later file,
d  causing merges and appends to break silently.
d
d  naam encodes once, saves the exact string-to-numeric mappings to
d  an Excel workbook, and reapplies them instantly to every
d  subsequent dataset, guaranteeing the same string always receives
d  the same numeric code. The Excel file also serves as a permanent,
d  human-readable audit record of every mapping in the project.
d
d  naam encode  : encode string variables and save mappings to Excel
d  naam apply   : reattach saved mappings; auto-register new categories
d  naam id      : convert string IDs to consistent numerics; saves mappings as .dta (no row limit)
d  naam export  : save value labels from an already-encoded dataset
d  naam list    : inspect a mapping file from inside Stata
d  naam decode  : reverse encoding -- numeric back to original strings
d  naam check   : verify in-memory labels against saved mapping (QA)
d  naam compare : compare two mapping files against each other
d
d  Inspired by codebookout (Das, 2014: S457811, Boston College).
d
d KW: encode
d KW: value labels
d KW: string variables
d KW: codebook
d KW: Excel
d KW: merge
d KW: panel data
d KW: ID variables
d KW: data quality
d
d Requires: Stata version 14
d
d Author: Vijayshree Jayaraman
